ive imperial projects. Tomoff argues that the spectacular Soviet successes in the system of international music competitions, taken together with the rapturous receptions accorded touring musicians, helped to persuade the Soviet leadership of the superiority of their system. This, combined with the historical triumphalism central to the Marxist-Leninist worldview, led to confidence that the USSR would be the inevitable winner in the global competition with the United States. Successes masked the fact that the very conditions that made them possible depended on a quiet process by which the USSR began to participate in an international legal and economic system dominated by the United States. Once the Soviet leadership transposed its talk of system superiority to the economic sphere, focusing in particular on consumer goods and popular culture, it had entered a competition that it could not win.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aCold WarxSocial aspectszSoviet Union. 0aMusic and statezSoviet UnionxHistory. 0aMusicxPolitical aspectszSoviet Union. 4aArt History. 4aMusical Arts & Ethnomusicology. 4aSoviet & East European History. 7aMUSIC / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  aSoviet music, Russian musicians, imperial competition, USSR, Soviet Union, Soviet leadership, popular culture, cultural Cold War, cultural studies, music competition, cultural competition, triumphalism, Marxist-Leninist worldview, competitive contemporary rhetoric of the US and Soviets.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060674440uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150170182540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501701825423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501701825/original  a978-3-11-060674-4  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Packa